{{Commonscat|Tsukiyama Kofun (Setouchi city)}}

'''Tsukiyama Kofun''' (築山古墳) is an ancient {{ill|kofun|ja|古墳|1=Kofun|12=draft|12=draft}} located in {{ill|Osafune Town|ja|長船町|12=draft|12=draft}}, {{ill|Setouchi, Okayama|ja|瀬戸内市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Okayama Prefecture. It is a {{ill|keyhole-shaped tumulus|ja|前方後円墳|1=Zenpokoenfun|12=draft|12=draft}}.

== Overview ==

Tsukiyama Kofun was constructed in the late {{ill|5th century|ja|5世紀|12=draft|12=draft}} to early {{ill|6th century|ja|6世紀|12=draft|12=draft}}. The tumulus measures approximately 82 meters in length, with the front section measuring 66 meters in width and 10 meters in height, and the rear circular section 38 meters in diameter and 9 meters in height. The tumulus was built by reshaping the tip of a hill extending to the north. The two-tiered mound features {{ill|haniwa|ja|埴輪|12=draft|12=draft}} arranged along its edges and base.

A vertical stone chamber was located at the center of the rear circular section. Constructed with rubble masonry, it was excavated in 1907 (Meiji 40), exposing a house-shaped sarcophagus. The sarcophagus, made of {{ill|tuff|ja|凝灰岩|12=draft|12=draft}}, was initially believed to be sourced from {{ill|Mount Nijō|ja|二上山|12=draft|12=draft}} on the Osaka-Nara border. However, recent studies indicate the material, known as "Aso Pink Stone," originates from {{ill|Uto City|ja|宇土市|12=draft|12=draft}}, Kumamoto Prefecture.

An excavation in 1988 (Shōwa 63) revealed the haniwa placement, paving stones of 15cm angular gravel, and a double moat surrounding the tumulus.

Artifacts uncovered include a divine-human image mirror, glass magatama, jasper cylindrical beads, iron swords, axes, straight swords, spears, halberds, arrowheads, armor, helmets, and horse fittings such as bits and pendants. These items are currently housed in the {{ill|Tokyo National Museum|ja|東京国立博物館|12=draft|12=draft}}.

The site was designated as a Historic Site of Okayama Prefecture on March 27, 1959.

== Sue Kodai Museum ==
Located adjacent to the tumulus's northern side, the Sue Kodai Museum opened in April 1996 (Heisei 8). Designed to resemble a raised-floor structure, the museum exhibits ceramics and artifacts from nearby kofun, the Nishitani archaeological site, Sue pottery kilns, and temple ruins. The museum is open on weekends and holidays from 9:30 AM to 5:00 PM (last entry at 4:30 PM). Admission is free. Address: 502-2 Nishisue, Osafune Town, Setouchi City, Okayama Prefecture.

== References ==
* Mino Norioka and Hiromi Gyōda (Eds.), Yoshio Kondo (Editor): ''Kibi Kofun Upper [Bizen, Mimasaka] – Kibi Archaeological Library 4,'' Kibito Publishing, 1996, pp. 22–24.
* Okayama Prefectural High School Social Studies Division, History Division (Ed.): ''New Edition: History Walks in Okayama Prefecture,'' Yamakawa Publishing, 1991, pp. 47–48.
* On-site pamphlet: ''Sue Ancient History Museum,'' Setouchi City Board of Education (Publisher).
* On-site explanation panel.
